Twitter Sentiment Comparison - Trump: Celebrity or Politician?¶

In this notebook I will gather Tweets from Trump as well as three celebrities and three politicians. I will go through the process of cleaning the Tweets by removing links, mentions, and punctuation. Once the data is clean I go through a wordcloud visualization, getting a sense of what words are often used by each user. After this qualitative exploration I perform a sentiment analysis using TextBlob for each user. The residual value between each user in a category (celebrity or politician) from Trump's sentiment score is squared, and the mean for each category is taken. A low residual score implies a more similar sentiment between Trump and the category.

# Function to access api
def get_api():
         
        # Authorization to consumer key and consumer secret
        auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
 
        # Access to user's access key and access secret
        auth.set_access_token(access_key, access_secret)
 
        # Calling api
        api = tweepy.API(auth)
 
        return api

Create a function that will create a Pandas dataframe for a given user containing a given number of tweets

In [8]:
def get_tweets(username, number_tweets):
    """Take in a Twitter handle and the number of Tweets to gather,
    return a Pandas dataframe with the tweet text"""
    tweets = extractor.user_timeline(screen_name=username, count=number_tweets)
    return pd.DataFrame(data=[tweet.text for tweet in tweets], columns=['Tweets'])

Cleaning Data¶

Below, regular expressions are used to match patterns for links and user mentions within tweets and replace them with an empty string. The processed tweet is returned. These functions are applied to the previously processed tweets and added as a column in the dataframe storing the tweets.

In [51]:
def remove_links(tweet):
    regex = re.compile("((https?):((//)|(\\\\))+([\w\d:#@%/;$()~_?\+-=\\\.&](#!)?)*)")
    line = regex.sub("", tweet)
    return line

Apply the remove links function to the celebrities, politicians, and Trump. Add this as a new column to each user's respective dataframe

In [52]:
for i in range(len(celebs)):
    celebs[i]["no links"] = celebs[i]['Tweets'].apply(remove_links)
    
for i in range(len(politicians)):
    politicians[i]["no links"] = politicians[i]['Tweets'].apply(remove_links)
    
Trump["no links"] = Trump['Tweets'].apply(remove_links)

Remove where a user mentions another user within a Tweet. Again do this for each user and create a new column for their dataframe. Each further step in cleaning should use the "most clean" Tweets available from the dataframe.

In [53]:
def remove_mentions(tweet):
    regex = re.compile('(^| )(@[^ \t]+)')
    return regex.sub("", tweet)

The remove_punctuations function takes in a tweet and uses string methods to remove punctuation, new line symbols, retweet signs and ampersands. Finally this changes all text to lowercase. This is applied to the previously most processed tweets, the ones where links and mentions have been removed.

In [58]:
def remove_punctuations(text):
    for punctuation in string.punctuation:
        text = text.replace(punctuation, '')
    text = text.replace('\n', '')
    text = text.replace('RT', '')
    text = text.replace('amp', '')
    return text.lower()

Now that all the Tweets have been processed, collect all tweets from a user into a single string for further analysis, starting with wordclouds.

In [63]:
# collect all tweets from a celeb for word clouds
# Each element in all_tweets has a string containing all tweets f

def make_tweet_string(list_of_dfs):
    
    all_tweets = []
    
    for i in range(len(list_of_dfs)):
        string_tweets = ''
        number_tweets = len(list_of_dfs[i]['processed tweets'])
        while number_tweets > 0:
            for tweet in list_of_dfs[i]['processed tweets']:
                string_tweets = string_tweets + " " + tweet
                number_tweets = number_tweets - 1
        all_tweets.append(string_tweets)
        
    return all_tweets

celeb_strings = make_tweet_string(celebs)
politician_strings = make_tweet_string(politicians)

def generate_wordclouds(tweet_string):
    
    wordcloud = WordCloud().generate(tweet_string)
    
    # lower max_font_size
    wordcloud = WordCloud(max_font_size=40).generate(tweet_string)
    plt.figure()
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")
    plt.axis("off")
    plt.show()
    return

Sentiment Analysis¶

Now that the cleaning and qualitative exploration is through, TextBlob will assign a numerical score measuring the sentiment of all the Tweets collected for a user.

In [70]:
def sentiment(strings):  
    sentiments = []
    for t in strings:
        tweet = TextBlob(t)
        sentiments = np.append(sentiments, tweet.sentiment.polarity)
    return sentiments
In [71]:
politician_sentiment = sentiment(politician_strings)

It seems from these plots that Trump's sentiment isn't quite like that of either group. It does seem to have the closest value to Cher's Tweets. This connection is intersting as back in the word cloud section, we saw that one of Cher's most commonly used words was Trump!

Given that visually it's not very striking that Trump's sentiment is very like or dislike either group, let's do a numerican comparison as well.

Take the difference between Trump's sentiment and each politician or celebrity, square this value (no negatives) and sum them together. This is one way to measure the sentiment difference between Trump and a group.

In [74]:
political_Trump = np.sum(((politician_sentiment - Trump_sentiment)**2))
In [75]:
celeb_Trump = np.sum((celeb_sentiment - Trump_sentiment)**2)

Conclusion¶

It seems that sentiment-wise, Trump's Tweets aren't quite like those of either group. From the plot with all sentiments it seemed that Trump's score was exceptionally low coompared to other users selected. This difference may be due to the celebrities and politicians chosen, but may be part of a larger trend. It cannot be determined from this sample. A larger and more diverse sampling may help make this distinction more clear. Even with this small sample size the sentiment differences reveal a smaller difference between Trump and the celebrities chosen. These scores are not significantly different though and this is not a strong connection. One of the most interesting findings was that Cher's Tweets and Trump's had the most similar sentiment score, and Cher writes of Trump often in her Tweets.

Run it again and maybe get different results if a user has Tweeted since the last time it was run! Add different users! More?
